A Republican strategy to counter Obama’s re-election
The Republican leaders justify their policies with the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter to be a myth, affirming that election fraud in the United States is less common than the number of people killed by the lightning strike.
Republican lawyers have only recorded 300 cases of electoral fraud in the U.S. in 10 years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on electoral participation.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the democratic system of the United States.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for conducting elections in the individual states.
In this sense, the majority of U.S. governments have been enacting new laws since 2009 that make it difficult to register or enter.
This phenomenon has gained significance after the November 2010 elections, which allowed 675 new Republican representatives to be registered in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills were introduced in 2011 alone, restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID and a proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also shorten the periods for early voting, invalidate the right to register as an elector on the day of the election, and grant citizens the right to vote for which a court act exists.
Before the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to raise such a claim.
In 2008, the Supreme Court of the United States confirmed the constitutionality of the Indiana law.
The Republican authorities rushed to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have promoted bills in 34 states, forcing voters to present a photo ID.
It is important to note that U.S. citizens, unlike Quebec, do not have a universal identification card like the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, i.e. 21 million eligible people, do not have a photo ID issued by a government authority in their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a passport.
However, it is often necessary to pay more than a hundred dollars to get the required passport.
Young people, minorities and low-income people are disproportionately affected by the new restrictions.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people with incomes of less than <0x24>35,000, 18% of citizens aged 65 and 20% of voters aged 18-29 do not have the required photo ID.
This is more than enough.
Students considered to be voters who vote for democratic candidates are not allowed to use their photo ID issued by their institution in several states.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of fishing or hunting associations who vote more strongly for the Republican side to use the cards issued by these associations for elections.
Before 2004, no state required a proof of citizenship for the election.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a claim.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove their U.S. citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting Hispanic votes.
It is obvious that two out of three Spanish voters prefer the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers in 2011 passed laws in eight states that abolished the registration of voters on election day.
In addition, you have restricted the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to those voters who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, campaigns to register voters in the 2004 general election have helped register about 10 million citizens.
Since the measures adopted since 2009, the share of new voter registration in 2010 has decreased by 17% compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers in five other states have passed laws aimed at shortening the period for early voting.
For example, in the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African-Americans, although they accounted for only 13% of the state’s voters.
The same applies to the Spanish population.
The latter accounted for only 11% of the voters, but 24% of the citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, the whites, which accounted for 76% of the voters, accounted for only 46% of the voters who voted in advance.
Of course, the democratic legislators and their supporters have vigorously opposed the adoption of laws restricting the registration of voters.
Several bills were blocked by the vetos of democratic governors.
The U.S. Attorney General has intervened to derogate the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
However, the newly introduced rules will undoubtedly make it difficult to exercise the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics applaud the party-political nature of the laws adopted and see in them as a clear goal the influence of the results in the decisive states for 2012.
A 2011 report by the Brennan Center shows that those states that have passed these laws make up 171 of the 270 votes required in the electorate to win the presidency.
It is too early to confirm with certainty that these changes to the legislation on the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on electoral participation.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the democratic system of the United States.
