The Higgs Boson analyzed
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs Boson has sparked some excitement last summer, and for good reason.
In fact, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence is predicted from the standard model - our best or "the least wrong" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - but has not yet been observed empirically.
But for physicists, it is not yet completely certain that it is really the Higgs.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it is very similar to the Higgs-Boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented at a major physics conference in Kyoto this week, but data is still lacking to be completely certain.
Nevertheless, let’s assume that it’s actually the Higgs, as there seems to be only a small risk of being fooled, and let’s look at what’s going on.
There is a law in this world that is necessarily inevitable, which causes two objects not to be present at the same place at the same time.
It is not possible to break this rule - and don't try it too hard as you will hurt yourself.
For even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that such a law applies to them as well: Pauli's principle of exclusion, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time, if they are in the same "quantum state" and if they are in the same "quantum state", and if they are in the same state, they are in their best condition.
Based on this, physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In a corner are the good citizens, who are called Fermione and politely obey the Pauli principle.
And on the other hand, the Bosons move, an evil gang of anarchists, to whom nothing is sacred – certainly not this principle, which means that they can actually be in the same place at the same time.
According to the website The Particle Adventure of the Berkeley Laboratories (which is absolutely amazing by the way) these bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons that we are not going to treat here and the "power particles" through which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson is somehow confused.
But it must be stressed here that these bosons are not all as exotic creatures as one might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, then only thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or the "particle of light", which is the "bot" of electromagnetic force.
In other words, if a particle accelerates with an electric charge or changes the direction, the electromagnetic field is "disturbed" precisely in this place, in a manner like a pebble thrown into a pond.
This "disruption" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon and thus one of the boson "carriers of force".
Stable field
The same goes for the Higgs Boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, has to be "disturbed" to show this boson.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the trigger must reach very high energies, somewhat similar to a frozen pond, whose surface could only be shattered by a very large rock.
That’s why a huge particle accelerator like CERN is required – the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a circumference of 27 km! – to achieve such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful in explaining the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others don’t – for example, a sheet of paper would never keep itself in the refrigerator.
And equally, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who do have a mass, while the others (like the photon) do not have a mass.
What can all this research be “good” for now, asks Mrs. Plamondon?
For science, they are used to check the standard model (SM), and they also allow physicists to carefully examine all the deviations between the observations and predictions of the SM.
By the way, there are many physicists who eagerly hope that such deviations will be found, since the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and stop some holes in the model.
It must be said that the latter still has major flaws as it does not provide an explanation for the gravity (ups!) and the dark matter that makes up about 80% of the matter of the universe (again ups!).
However, such deviations have not been found at CERN so far.
Consequences
The impact of these researches on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that it does not exist.
By the way, in the early 1960s, the pioneers of the laser in the Bell laboratories did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the deceased physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who even in 1962 developed the first permanent strip laser (the first were pulsed) - has already been said that the laser was seen at the beginning rather than a "Labor game."
Just imagine...
In addition, applications can also result from all the instruments surrounding the research.
For example, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969 during his work in optics.
Although it was not the original purpose, today this sensor serves all digital cameras around the world as an "eye" and was awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily change our lives, but it does mean that one can never really know...
Palliative care - the best way to die... <0x7C> Le Devoir
With its Committee on "Death in Dignity", Quebec recently discussed the delicate question of the living.
