A few weeks ago, Mr. L. lived alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that took him up had given him a two-year term.
"They gave me five years to live, I managed seven years," he said half-heartedly, lying in his bed in the palliative care home of Victor-Gadbois in Beloeil, where he had arrived the day before.
"But it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for it," he says.
The disease does its job: an immense weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating himself.
Sitting at the table before a delicious lunch, he resigns to let himself be helped with the meal.
Courageously, he even manages to smile and talk to the strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medicines, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
“My biggest wish is that you cure my diarrhea because it’s humiliating,” he said.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
“Over the course of our lives, we learn that a man is pinching while standing,” says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at Victor-Gadbois’ home.
Returning to childhood is an unacceptable humiliation for some people.
"It depends on the person's ability to take a step back," he notes.
Because in the opinion of several people working in palliative care, major events take place amid these retreats.
Patients who are admitted to the home for palliative care Victor-Gadbois all suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, they are no longer overwhelmed by the doctors and nurses who take care of them with so-called "healing" care.
For Ms. A., 89, the worst fear is to die "consciously and by drowning".
But because of the disease, I really got to know my children.
“I have good children,” she adds.
“I don’t have any desires in life anymore,” she says before accepting that you put on a mask that helps you breathe.
In the next few days, she is still waiting for the last visit of her son, who comes from Italy.
In the Victor-Gadbois home, a group of volunteers are offered body care and assistance in eating.
Palliative care is used when there are no other options.
To make death more enjoyable.
In Quebec, there is a palliative care bed for 11,700 people.
This is very little given that one day we will all die.
Here, life continues under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the home.
At the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The dying person is given oral care with brandy or pepsi, depending on their preference.
Diabetics no longer need to control their blood sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Yesterday evening we served Mr. X a beer that died in the course of the night.
This morning his son will drink the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We are helping relatives and patients equally," says Nursing Director Nathalie Savard.
In Victor Gadbois, there is no day like the other.
In addition to an old man of 93 years who enjoys the last family reunion in the yard and is well supported by his head pillows, while attacking to his honour, a young man of 36 years dies, who has passed away from his parents, his wife and his two little children.
“For six months, three to five beds have always been covered with cancer patients under the age of 45,” says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of patients admitted to the Victor Gadbois home come from their home, 47% from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, i.e. to a care that is intended to alleviate the suffering of patients when they have reached the final stage of their life, either at home, in a hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois Home and the Society for Home Palliative Care in the Greater Montreal area, are more or less exclusively specialized in the care of cancer patients.
It is this great inadequacy in Quebec’s health care that makes it possible for several doctors specializing in palliative care to take care of the passing of a law to regulate death aid and assisted suicide with concern.
Since October, a manifesto has been circulating, signed by prominent palliative care figures such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe to express their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health system is not powerful enough to ensure that everyone has the right to high-quality palliative care before accepting to switch to death care.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who had been in the emergency room with great pain for 14 days without taking measures to relieve her.
I fear that the patients just want to die because they don’t get adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists treat their patients, despite the worst prognosis, to the last day.
Hélène Richard’s chances of survival were already minimal when she cancelled a troublesome chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was going to stop the treatment, she told me she regretted giving up the fight.
However, she told me that I was in the end!
No Omnipotent Care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who have asked to die thank the nursing staff for not fulfilling this wish after their pain has been relieved by a palliative care team.
It must be said, however, that palliative care is not omnipotent in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, head of the home palliative care company of the Montreal area, 8% of patients don’t talk about pain treatment.
Thus, at the end of life, doctors often resort to terminal sedation, which leads to either sporadically or permanently sleeping the patient until the time of his death.
We can no longer act as if we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly have the opportunity to resort to this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not relieved all say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But that doesn’t necessarily mean, “I want you to fall asleep,” but “I want my pain to be relieved.”
