After the price of Bitcoin reached a peak of <0x24>30 (<0xE2><0x82><0xAC>23) in June 2011, it fell to <0x24>2 five months later before recovering to around <0x24>10 today (the rates are listed on bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing particularly impressive compared to the world trade of real currencies or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) has shown interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
She describes Bitcoin as "the virtual currency with the greatest success", "in competition with the dollar or the euro" and "similar to conventional currencies".
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies such as “credits” that are used to advance in a video game that you can win or buy through games (and sometimes even exchange back).
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, trade is monitored and processed every time by a central authority.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously account holders, auditors, money issuers as well as buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Any transaction between two users is actually carried out between two email addresses in the form of an email.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A series of data associated with this transaction is electronically signed by a dual encryption system.
In this way, the network can verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Using the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the traded Bitcoins are present in the accounting book of public accounts distributed throughout the network.
The decisive step is to include this new transaction in this book.
This is done through a mathematical task that is started on the computers, with the winner, who is a kind of provisional central banker, having the privilege to add this additional line.
It is a fragment of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and unique electronic fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole is "defeated".
The goal is to find the number that results in a special fingerprint (many zeroes at the beginning).
If this number has been found, the other nodes can easily check if it is the right one.
The transaction is thus permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If a user wants to pay for scams twice very quickly (less than 10 minutes) with the same money, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other remains unlinked as both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the task gets 50 Bitcoins.
In order to prevent inflation, this reward is regularly halved, probably before the end of 2012.
The bitcoins in circulation are thus limited to 21 million, but can be divided up to one hundred million units, which leaves a certain amount of room for play.
In addition, the difficulty of the task is increased with each improvement in computing performance.
The life of the network has already had heights and depths.
The websites that provide services for Bitcoin were attacked and the Bitcoin deposits were stolen.
“The vulnerability used does not concern the actual protocol,” assures Pierre Noizat, who has just introduced a paymium that is a real-money payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
