Yet many citizens of the Central Asian republics, who want to make their money in Russia, admit that they are not only unable to speak the language of the target country, but can hardly express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault as the evil: only a few Turkmen, Uzbeks and Tajiks can afford only reasonable basic education.
For there is not even money in their families to feed the children, except to buy them decent clothes, shoes, and school supplies.
As a teenager, these children immediately took the first opportunity to make money.
"It's difficult without language skills," they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
Citizens’ rights underline the following important aspect of the law.
Only migrants with legal status are required to pass the test.
If you do not have this status, there is no examination and therefore no official work.
In the meantime, most of the guest workers remain illegal in Russia.
"Welcome" or "Access Banned for Unauthorized"
