Poland and space.
Last week, Poland was admitted as the 20th member of the European Space Agency (ESA) at a Council of Ministers meeting of the European Space Agency (ESA), making it the second member of the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a member of the ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland began a close cooperation with the ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
Poland’s journey into space, of course, began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish space enthusiasts engaged in space travel, with which they did not always come to terms.
I remember here, for example, the lecture by A. <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld on December 6, 1933, at the Warsaw Observatory, where the author presented ideas from his pioneering work "Entrance to Cosmonautics".
However, the ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the listeners cold, and after years <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld still remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
In 1934, <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld won the Prix REP Hirsch, founded by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch for "Entrance to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important advocate of astronomy and space travel.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski’s world-renowned contribution to the development of spacecraft was appreciated, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the Earth-oriented side of the moon was named after him.
Already in 1925 a railway drasine was built in Poland, for which a rocket propulsion was planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the draft and the details of this project remained unknown.
It is not yet clear whether the missile should be used to launch or brake the Draisine.
The information about this comes exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began to deal with rocket-powered shootings.
The research was conducted by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustav Mokrzyckiegi.
From the submitted documents, it is clear that the research was advanced until the stage of practical tests.
The research was then freely interrupted by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937 appeared in the specialist press of the design of a photoelectric hunting missile from Ing. Rohozi<0xC5><0x84>ski, and the following year the work "Raketa - torpedo powietrzna i rakitobomba lotnicza" by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects focused on the military use of the missile propulsion.
Shortly before the war, all projects for the military use of rocket technology were coordinated by the Interim Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy).
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of activity, its work was completed from the beginning of the war.
After the war, more articles on space were published in the Polish press thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautcycny).
The first mention of this company is made in 1954 in the November issue of the journal Problemy, in which four extensive articles are devoted to space.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal to establish a space company.
At the time, there were already the first projects on satellite technology, and it was anticipated that space exploration would have a future.
Already in its beginnings in 1956, the Polish space company PTA endeavoured to join the International Space Federation founded in 1951, and in fact, the PTA became a regular member already in the autumn of 1956.
The following year, the first PTA chairman, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became deputy chairman of the International Federation for Space.
He held this office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been instrumental in the development of the highly successful meteorological rocket (Raketa Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The missile with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and weighed not quite 5 kg.
Later an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959 began flight tests in the B<0xC5><0x82><0xC4><0x99>dow Desert with the two-stage rocket RM-2.
The missile was 1.4 m long and weighed approximately 11.5 kg.
Another stage of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 should reach a flight altitude of up to 14.5 km and be used for the observation of altitude winds.
However, in 1962 the further development was stopped.
The Meteor-1 was the successor to the first RM-type rockets developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage missile, with a total length of 510 cm and a start weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed from these rockets, which differed in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A missile had a 0.4-litre transport space, Meteor-1B over 0.34-litre and Meteor-1C over 0.62-litre.
The maximum flight altitude for all three types was 37 km.
In the years 1965 to 1968, the Meteor-2 rockets were developed at the Institute of Aviation, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg at an altitude of approximately 60 km.
After that, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland’s accession to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, followed by the establishment of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
Poland also participated in space exploration with Soviet satellites as part of the Intercosmos program, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslav Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after the Czech Vladimir Remek.
