In November 1979, a mob of demonstrating Islamist students occupied the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats as hostages.
For their release, they demanded the extradition of the fallen Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the United States after the revolution, which had kept the patronage over his regime for decades.
There was no positive way out of this situation for the American government - she could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, as this would have massively damaged the trust of her allies in other countries.
At the same time, she was unable to implement the liberation of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a heavy blow to the reputation of the United States, and the subsequent fiasco in the violent attempt to liberate hostages made everything even worse.
The captured diplomats were finally released after 444 days after negotiations were negotiated by the Algerian government.
The fate of the hostages at home highlighted a wave of solidarity as well as anti-Iranian moods.
Debacle in Iran contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter's defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo by director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story that gave the U.S. a small partial victory.
Just before the embassy was occupied, six embassy staff managed to escape.
This ended after numerous complications in the Canadian Ambassador's residence.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to bring the refugees out of Iran, helping them with an extravagant story to hide their true identity – they traveled blinded with Canadian passports as members of a film staff who allegedly rode in the country for a science-fiction film.
Combination of genres
The plan developed by the expert for "Exfiltration", Tony Mendez, also required Hollywood's cooperation.
To make the filming credible, articles about this film project appeared in journals, press conferences were held, and the fictional production company had a real office.
The details of this operation have been kept secret for a long time. The film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand, he is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time also a so-called "Caper Movie", i.e. the story of a successful cast, such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
This changes the mood levels in the film - on the one hand the documentary scenes from Tehran (the title sequence shows iconic contemporary photographs, and there are no big differences in film footage of the same situations).
On the other hand, the loose passages from Hollywood that come ironically and easily oversized therefore.
And then there's the scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions -- men in suits at the meeting table, on the office floor, on the phone...
Ben Affleck made a remarkable reboot of his career with this film.
A smiling actor has become a respectable director, and even as an actor he is no longer the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third film after Krimi No Children's Play (Gone Baby Gone, 2007) and the Thriller City Without Mercy (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck's first film not to play in the director's home Boston.
The feeling for the atmosphere of the place was one of the features that the previous films of this director overtook from the standard Hollywoods.
However, Affleck also proves this feeling in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film play in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that really took place - the initial sequence of the shock of the message is very impressive in its clarity, and still conveys the feeling of confusion and unpredictability.
A similar effect is achieved by Affleck with his team even in fictitious scenes (the wrong film staff on a basar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story does not actually offer many exciting scenes in the cinematic sense.
But with a few, he works quite successfully, sometimes helping out the reality – which doesn’t always seem so elegant (the scenes in which the threatening crisis at Tehran airport is diverted from a telephone call in America, or even the chase on the start-up track, seem somewhat disrupted).
The weakness of Argo is its too wide dispersion, which is due to the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood collaborators, but their characters deserved more space, and so they are far from alone in the film.
Affleck’s film loses some traction, which is a film that can be followed with a certain interest and with it the design and the retro style reminiscent of a thriller from the 1970s.
Enthusiasm, however, only arouses difficulty.
