The prosecutor’s office on Friday tried to find that Army-free Bradley Manning — accused of the largest disclosure of confidential information in U.S. history — missed several occasions to complain about the alleged abuse he committed in military custody.
At Manning’s cross-examination during a preliminary hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Maj. Ashden Fein explained that documents on weekly visits made by prison officials during Manning’s nine-month detention in Quantico, Virginia, did not show any complaints about his treatment.
A day before the cross-examination, which was held as a result of a request by the defence to dismiss the charge – Manning had already been sufficiently punished by the hard detention period – Manning had said that he had considered suicide in prison.
The U.S. military intelligence analyst, who was arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The material was then published by WikiLeaks on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed Manning as the source of the information.
In the hearing on Friday, Fein and Manning passed the forms that officials had filled out after their meeting with Manning during his detention in the Quantico Military Prison, where he had entered from July 2010 to April 2011 under increased conditions of detention.
The officials asked Manning questions and wrote down his answers.
When Fine asked him about the forms on Friday, Manning admitted that he had judged the treatment by his guards as "excellent" and the treatment by the facility as "very professional".
The forms, so refined, contained no complaints about abuse, although officials had asked Manning directly about his treatment.
Manning replied that he had expressed his concerns orally and the officials had discussed them with him and indicated to deal with them, but they had not been recorded.
"They wrote (after meeting the concerns) 'No problems,' and that didn't necessarily mean I didn't say anything at all," Manning said.
The judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he didn’t complain about his treatment when he met with a committee in January 2011 to investigate the suicidal thoughts he mentioned a few months earlier on a form.
Manning replied that his intention during this meeting was to reduce his observation status to “prevention of injuries.”
The military said it had assigned him this restrictive status – which is a level of suicide threat – to his and the protection of others.
"I wanted to convince employees that I was doing well, and get rid of the observation status to prevent injuries (...) to achieve a higher quality of life from my point of view," Manning said.
Manning said on Thursday about his arrest and detention in Kuwait, where he was detained for about two months before being transferred to the prison of Quantico Marine Base in Virginia in July 2010.
He said in Kuwait he had considered suicide and had become unconscious due to the heat.
Not knowing what is going on with him or in the outside world has been a burden.
"My world shrinked on Camp Arafjon, on this cage together," Manning said on Thursday.
I thought I'd die in this cage.
When moved to Quantico, Manning spent most of his days in a small cell – at least 21 hours and often more than 23 hours – and without company.
He was only allowed a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, clothes and his glasses.
Manning said he tried to stay in motion because on the day it was forbidden to sleep or just lie down.
He always had to sleep with light that penetrated his cell from the outside.
When he turned around at night and could no longer see his face, he was awakened so that he turned back.
In January 2011, Mannings's lawyer formally raised objections to Mannings' treatment.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to the military prison of Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
On Friday, Judge Manning also questioned a charge he had raised in his statement on Thursday — so he had to sleep naked one night in his cell in Quantico and must stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners at a morning count.
Manning had stated that during this counting he had never had the opportunity to cover himself with his ceiling.
During the interrogation on Friday, Manning admitted that he had been ordered by his guard to drop the ceiling he could have covered himself with, but he admitted that no one had asked him to do so.
Manning said on Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before, and had previously tried to show an official that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning told the official that he could have used the ligament of his underpants or his flip-flops to hurt himself, but he did not.
That night, Manning said, his underpants, flip-flops and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least consider his experiences of imprisonment and drastically reduce his level of imprisonment, should he be convicted in his trial before the military court, which is set for the beginning of next year.
The defense has stated that Manning will plead guilty to minor offences, while other allegations deemed too extreme should be challenged.
The continuation of the hearing is scheduled for this weekend. The Prosecutor's Office is expected to justify the conditions of detention.
The Pentagon maintains in its position that Manning has been detained in accordance with the provisions applicable to all prisoners held under the highest security measures in Quantico.
The allegations against Manning include favoring the enemy, illegally publishing intelligence on the Internet, transferring national defense information, and theft of public property or documents.
If he is found guilty in all charges, he will be sentenced to life in prison.
My Mexican-American Identity Crisis.
