I grew up in Central California and have been called "Mexican" my whole life.
An ethnic shortcut - just as my friends in Boston call themselves "Irene" or my friends in New York "Italian".
Later, I chose "Mexican-American".
But this was Mexico.
And in my grandfather’s home there was no need for shortcuts or ties.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish, at least good enough to assert myself in this language at both ends of an interview.
But I don’t have the vocabulary of a native speaker, and my American accent is not going away either.
So I took my American passport and put myself in the trap for extraterrestrials.
I thought about that moment this week when the future Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
The agenda included all those issues that one would expect when the heads of the two countries met: immigration, drugs and trade.
Pena Nieto was also very interested in talking about the growth of the Mexican economy, which is a reason why Mexicans today are equally likely to stay in Mexico rather than emigrate to the United States.
He wants to ally himself with the United States and Canada and create a North American trade bloc in the role of the European Union.
And Pena Nieto vowed to continue Mexico’s war against the drug cartels, even though he did not mention any details about it.
Mexico's relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans probably never waste a single thought of the fact that the United States entered Mexico in 1848 and forced the country’s leadership under gun control to leave more than half of their territory to them.
But for Mexicans who think in centuries and not in minutes, memories of this event cannot be overlooked.
So once an official of the U.S. government exercises even the mildest criticism of Mexico, one hears – in the Mexican press and among the country’s elites – complaints about how Americans oppress the sovereignty of their neighboring country.
And the children of Montezuma are on the war path.
And yet Mexico’s biggest challenge lies in fact in its relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican Americans living in the United States.
Want to talk about resentments?
There's more than enough.
Mexico has winners and losers, people for whom the country offers opportunities, and others for whom it does not.
The only reason why so many people of Mexican descent live in cities such as Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is that at some point in our tree, a person - perhaps a parent or grandparental part - did not get a chance in Mexico and headed north.
And in most cases, this person corresponded to a profile - dark-skinned, untrained, from a poor village, etc.
We are the descendants of these people, and our loyalty is to them.
Not Mexico.
And although we may now live the American dream, have attended good schools and got good jobs, we must never lose sight of the American dream we live – not the Mexican one.
Our identity may sometimes disappear, but as far as our loyalty is concerned, this is not the case.
This clearly applies to the United States.
In addition, we are aware that we do not like many members of the Mexican leadership.
This is based on reciprocity.
They see us as a reminder of a humiliating defeat and look down on us because we are not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our ties to Mexico will never be strong enough.
In your opinion, our existence is a symbol of failure.
If our families hadn't failed in Mexico, they wouldn't have gone.
And then we wouldn't be caught behind the silk curtain - with a pleasant life in the United States, but somehow lost.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and legally immigrated to the United States as a child, reminds me that there are tensions between Mexicans and Mexican Americans because Mexicans have a clearer idea of who they are - and Mexican Americans take those.
While she is a U.S. citizen, she sees herself as part of two countries.
But many Mexican Americans I know feel like they don’t belong to either country or any other country.
We love the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
You enjoy the best of both worlds, but none of them is rooted in them.
In Mexico, we are seen as Americans.
And in the United States, we are seen as Mexicans.
As I should learn during my journey, there is something that makes this relationship even more complicated: Some Mexican leaders and parts of the educational bourgeoisie want to reconnect with the diaspora.
They want to employ Mexican Americans as provisional "ambassadors" for Mexico, representing their interests in the United States.
We should tell our American colleagues how great it is to visit this country and put pressure on the political leadership to intensify their ties to Mexico.
Well, now.
That's not gonna happen.
Too many hurt feelings.
And given the unfair distribution of income, unbalanced corruption and drug violence, many of us are not so sure if this is really a great country.
I'm afraid you'll have to go through that alone, Amigos.
That's fair.
If at least some Mexicans are not ready to forgive the United States for dealing with Mexico a century and a half ago, they must also accept that some Mexican Americans have a grudge about how their family members were treated not so long ago.
Hmmm.
Maybe we're "mexican" more than I thought.
