The company is PT Candi Ngrimbi, who since 1960 has been exploiting the volcano and (not to mention) its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 Eurocent) for each kilogram of sulfur.
That then sells them for 10,000 rupees (83 Eurocent) to the petrochemical industry, because this mineral is widely used in everyday life and is used for the manufacture of timber, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even for the bleaching of sugar.
"Since we normally carry 70 kg, we get about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each route," explains Anto, who usually makes three routes a day.
For each route, it takes three hours to complete, but at the end of the day it has 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros).
What seems like a miserable wage for such a seemingly inhuman effort is three times what he would earn with field work.
"The daily salary of the miners here, where the coffee harvest is paid 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) per day and the average monthly income is two million rupees (167 euros), is very high," explains the carrier, who previously worked as a Maurer on the tourist island of Bali.
There he earned 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day, and the work was not so hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a nearby village, and for a reason that is as important in Indonesia as sulfur: "I married a girl from Bali, I married her to Islam, where they are Java, and they are Hindus."
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated because of the toxic gas.
The 27-year-old Anto has been putting his life at risk at Kawah Ijen for three years, whose sulfur has already left the first traces of him, although he covers his face with a mask and special glasses.
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated due to the toxic gas from the volcano.
This is the price he has to pay for achieving his dream.
